bib_record.title: Total kinetic energy and mass yields from the fast neutron-induced fission of 239Pu

free_txt: Experiment was conducted at the WNR
facility at Los Alamos National Lab using Flight Path
Twin arrays of nine 1 cm2 Si PIN diodes arranged
in a 3 x 3 square were located to the downstream left
and upstream right of the neutron beam, The two
arrays were 180 deg apart in the laboratory frame.
Experiment was conducted at the WNR
facility at Los Alamos National Lab using Flight Path
Neutrons with white spectrum were produced by
spallation of a thick tungsten target by 800 MeV
protons.
Incident neutron energy was measured by time of
flight. The proton beam was structured in the form of
625 mu-s macropulses with a repetition rate of
100-120 Hz. Each macropulse was composed of 0.25 ns
wide micropulses separated by 1800 ns. The distance
from spallation source to 239Pu target was
Circular target of 58.0 mu-g/cm2
239PuF4 with radius of 1 cm was deposited by the
vapor deposition method onto approx. 100 mu-g/cm2
carbon foil. The carbon foil was previously glued to
an aluminum frame
Origin of uncertainties not described
